Therefore, it is sufficient to prove that $\sum_{i=1}^{4} \frac{1}{a_{i}+s} \leqslant \frac{4}{9} \sum_{1 \leqslant i<j \leqslant 4} \frac{1}{\left(s-a_{i}\right)+\left(s-a_{j}\right)}$. Let $a_{1}=a, a_{2}=b, a_{3}=c, a_{4}=d$, the above inequality is equivalent to
$$\begin{array}{l}
\frac{2}{9}\left(\frac{1}{a+b}+\frac{1}{a+c}+\frac{1}{a+d}+\frac{1}{b+c}+\frac{1}{b+d}+\frac{1}{c+d}\right) \geqslant \\
\frac{1}{3 a+b+c+d}+\frac{1}{a+3 b+c+d}+\frac{1}{a+b+3 c+d}+\frac{1}{a+b+c+3 d}
\end{array}$$

By the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality, we have
$$\begin{array}{l}
(3 a+b+c+d)\left(\frac{1}{a+b}+\frac{1}{a+c}+\frac{1}{a+d}\right) \geqslant 9 \\
\frac{1}{9}\left(\frac{1}{a+b}+\frac{1}{a+c}+\frac{1}{a+d}\right) \geqslant \frac{1}{3 a+b+c+d}
\end{array}$$

Similarly, we get
$$\begin{array}{l}
\frac{1}{9}\left(\frac{1}{a+b}+\frac{1}{b+c}+\frac{1}{b+d}\right) \geqslant \frac{1}{a+3 b+c+d} \\
\frac{1}{9}\left(\frac{1}{a+c}+\frac{1}{b+c}+\frac{1}{c+d}\right) \geqslant \frac{1}{a+b+3 c+d} \\
\frac{1}{9}\left(\frac{1}{a+d}+\frac{1}{b+d}+\frac{1}{c+d}\right) \geqslant \frac{1}{a+b+c+3 d}
