When $n=1$, the inequality obviously holds.
Assume that when $n=k$, the conclusion holds for any $k$ positive numbers. When $n=k+1$, for any $k+1$ positive numbers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \cdots, a_{k}, a_{k+1}$, according to the induction hypothesis, we have $\sqrt{a_{2}+a_{3}+\cdots+a_{k+1}}+\sqrt{a_{3}+a_{4}+\cdots+a_{k+1}}+$ $\sqrt{a_{4}+\cdots+a_{k+1}}+\cdots+\sqrt{a_{k+1}} \geqslant \sqrt{a_{2}+4 a_{3}+9 a_{4}+\cdots+k^{2} a_{k+1}}$.

Therefore, $\sqrt{a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{k+1}}+\sqrt{a_{2}+a_{3}+\cdots+a_{k+1}}+\sqrt{a_{3}+a_{4}+\cdots+a_{k+1}}+$ $\sqrt{a_{4}+\cdots+a_{k+1}}+\cdots+\sqrt{a_{k+1}} \geqslant \sqrt{a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{k+1}}+\sqrt{a_{2}+4 a_{3}+9 a_{4}+\cdots+k^{2} a_{k+1}}$

It suffices to prove $\sqrt{a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{k+1}}+\sqrt{a_{2}+4 a_{3}+9} \overline{a_{4}+\cdots+k^{2} a_{k+1}} \geqslant$ $\sqrt{a_{1}+4 a_{2}+9 a_{3}+\cdots+k^{2} a_{k}+(k+1)^{2} a_{k+1}}$

Squaring and rearranging, it suffices to prove
$$\begin{array}{l}
\sqrt{a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{k+1}} \cdot \sqrt{a_{2}+4 a_{3}+9 a_{4}+\cdots+k^{2} a_{k+1}} \geqslant \\
a_{2}+2 a_{3}+3 a_{4}+\cdots+k a_{k+1}
\end{array}$$

By the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality, we have
$$\begin{array}{l}
\left(a_{2}+a_{3}+\cdots+a_{k+1}\right)\left(a_{2}+4 a_{3}+9 a_{4}+\cdots+k^{2} a_{k+1}\right) \geqslant \\
\left(a_{2}+2 a_{3}+3 a_{4}+\cdots+k a_{k+1}\right)^{2}
\end{array}$$

Thus,
$$\begin{array}{l}
\left(a_{1}+a_{2}+a_{3}+\cdots+a_{k+1}\right)\left(a_{2}+4 a_{3}+9 a_{4}+\cdots+k^{2} a_{k+1}\right) \geqslant \\
\left(a_{2}+2 a_{3}+3 a_{4}+\cdots+k a_{k+1}\right)^{2}
\end{array}$$

That is,
$$\begin{array}{l}
\sqrt{a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{k+1}} \cdot \sqrt{a_{2}+4 a_{3}+9 a_{4}+\cdots+k^{2} a_{k+1}} \geqslant \\
a_{2}+2 a_{3}+3 a_{4}+\cdots+k a_{k+1}
\end{array}$$

Therefore, when $n=k+1$, the inequality holds. Hence, by induction, the inequality is proved.

