\[
1 + \frac{1}{2^l} + \frac{1}{3^l} + \ldots + \frac{1}{(n-1)^2} \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{1}{2^l} + \frac{1}{3^l} + \ldots + \frac{1}{(n-1)^2} + \frac{1}{n^l}
\]

and the area of the curvilinear trapezoid \(ABCD\) is \(\frac{1 - \frac{1}{n^l}}{l-1}\) (see the solution to problem 148a)). From this, it follows that

\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{1}{2^l} + \frac{1}{3^2} + \ldots + \frac{1}{(n-1)^2} + & \frac{1}{n^2} < \frac{1 - \frac{1}{n^2}}{l-1} < \\
& < 1 + \frac{1}{2^2} + \frac{1}{3^l} + \ldots + \frac{1}{(n-1)^k}
\end{aligned}
\]

or

\[
\frac{1 - \frac{1}{n^l}}{l-1} < 1 + \frac{1}{2^2} + \frac{1}{3^i} + \ldots + \frac{1}{(n-1)^2} < \frac{1 - \frac{1}{n^l}}{l-1} + 1 - \frac{1}{n^2}
\]

or, finally,

\[
\frac{1}{l-1} - \frac{1}{l-1} \frac{1}{n^l} < 1 + \frac{1}{2^l} + \frac{1}{3^l} + \ldots + \frac{1}{(n-1)^l} < \frac{l}{l-1} - \frac{1}{l-1} \frac{1}{n^l}
\]

Since \(\frac{1}{n^\eta} \rightarrow 0\) as \(n \rightarrow \infty\), it follows from this inequality that the statement of the problem is true (that the sum \(1 + \frac{1}{2^z} + \frac{1}{3^\iota} + \ldots + \frac{1}{n^2}\) tends to a certain limit as \(n \rightarrow \infty\) follows from the fact that it increases with \(n\) and always remains less than \(\frac{l}{l-1}\)).

