10. Proof: Let $p_{i}$ be a common prime factor of $a, b$, $q_{i}$ be a prime factor only of $a$, and $r_{k}$ be a prime factor only of $b$, then
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\varphi(a b)=a b \prod_{i}\left(1-\frac{1}{p_{i}}\right) \prod_{j}\left(1-\frac{1}{q_{j}}\right) \prod_{k}\left(1-\frac{1}{r_{k}}\right) \\
\varphi^{2}\left(a^{2}\right) \varphi^{2}\left(b^{2}\right)=\left[a^{2} \prod_{i}\left(1-\frac{1}{p_{i}}\right) \prod_{j}\left(1-\frac{1}{q_{j}}\right)\right]\left[b^{2} \prod_{i}\left(1-\frac{1}{p_{i}}\right) \prod_{k}\left(1-\frac{1}{r_{k}}\right)\right] \\
\mathrm{Q} \prod_{j}\left(1-\frac{1}{q_{j}}\right) \prod_{k}\left(1-\frac{1}{r_{k}}\right) \leq 1, \therefore(\varphi(a b))^{2} \leq \varphi\left(a^{2}\right) \varphi\left(b^{2}\right) \\
\therefore \varphi(a b) \leq \sqrt{\varphi\left(a^{2}\right) \varphi\left(b^{2}\right)} \leq \sqrt{\frac{\varphi^{2}\left(a^{2}\right)+\varphi^{2}\left(b^{2}\right)}{2}}, \text { hence the conclusion holds. }
\end{array}
$$

